rizon. The plethora of research on Sagittarius A* since its discovery in 1974 has long seemed an interwoven pattern of loose threads. No one has successfully synthesized this growing body of work into a manageable, coherent book both for professional researchers and for students taking courses focusing on black holes and galactic nuclei--until now. With Fulvio Melia's The Galactic Supermassive Black Hole, readers finally have at their disposal a one-volume crucible of essential ideas, logically streamlined but with thorough references for those wishing to explore the various topics in greater depth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBlack holes (Astronomy). 7aSCIENCE / Astronomy.2bisacsh  aBoltzmann equation.  aCerenkov radiation.  aChristoffel symbols.  aCoulomb forces.  aEinstein ring.  aEulerian perturbations.  aGalilean relativity.  aLorentz boost.  aNewtonian gravity.  aOhmic diffusion.  aaccelerated frame.  aaccretion filaments.  aangular broadening.  aanomalous resistivity.  aanomalous viscosity.  aarea amplification.  aballoon instruments.  abandwidth.  abipolar outflow.  abirefringence.  ablack hole image.  acircular polarization.  acontravariant tensor.  adiffusion equation.  adisk magnetic field.  adusty gas.  adynamical center.  aelectric field.  aenergy-at-infinity.  aframe dragging.  afree-free emission.  agalactic center.  agravitational confinement.  ahydrodynamic simulations.  aindex of refraction.  ainertia.  ainfalling clouds.  ainitial mass function.  airon-line emission.  akinematic viscosity.  amagnetic flare.  amagnetized accretion.  aneutron stars.  aorbital companion.  aphotodissociation.  aphoton geodesic.  apolarized emission.  aprotostars.  aquiescent luminosity.  arelative motion.  aseconda